Always subtract the largest possible Roman value from the number and append its symbol. Keep doing this until the number becomes 0.
This works because Roman numerals are built from largest to smallest values.
Roman numerals are formed by subtracting the largest possible symbol value each time. I maintain parallel arrays for values and symbols in descending order, 
including subtractive combinations like 900 and 4. Then I greedily subtract while appending symbols.

class Solution {
    public String intToRoman(int num) {
        int[] values = { 1000, 900, 500, 400, 100, 90, 50, 40, 10, 9, 5, 4, 1};
        String[] symbols = {
            "M", "CM", "D", "CD",
            "C", "XC", "L", "XL",
            "X", "IX", "V", "IV", "I"
        };
        StringBuilder result = new StringBuilder();
        for (int i = 0; i < values.length; i++) {
            while (num >= values[i]) {
                result.append(symbols[i]);
                num -= values[i];
            }
        }
        return result.toString();
    }
}
